{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957112701/1021.xml":{"full_text":"A-4\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington, D. C.\nDR. HOUSTON H. MERRITT\nAssists in Diagnosis\n\u2014AP Photo\nTEXT OF DIAGNOSIS\nPresident's Physicians\nReport on Findings\nThe following bulletin on President Eisenhower\u2019s ill\n\u25a0ness was issued at the White House at 3 p.m. yesterday,\nsigned by Mai. Oen. Howard M. Snyder, the President's\npersonal physician, and Mai. Oen. Leonard D. Heaton, the\ncommandant at Walter Reed Hospital:\nAt 1 pjn. yesterday, upon\nthe President\u2019s return to the\nWhite House following the re\nception at the airport of the\nKing of Morocco, and the pa\nrade through Washington to\nthe President\u2019s guesthouse, the\nPresident told Mrs. Eisenhower\nand Gen. Snyder that he felt a\nchill. He went to his dressing\nroom immediately, and when\nhe lay down to rest, asked for\nan additional blanket and a\nhot water bottle.\nThe President went to his\noffice at 2:40 p.m\u201e following his\nrest period and lunch. He did\nnot feel well, and returned to\nhis dressing room where Gen.\nSnyder joined him. He un\ndressed and went to bed, and\nagain asked for an additional\nblanket and hot water bottle.\nGen. Snyder was Joined by Col.\nWalter R. Tkach, and subse\nquently by Col. Francis W.\nPruitt, the consultant in in\nternal medicine in the office of\nthe Surgeon General of the\nArmy, Gen. Heaton; Col. Mat\ntingly, and Lt. Col. Roy E.\nClausen, jr., chief of the neu\nrological service at Walter Reed\nHospital. Examination by these\nphysicians disclosed the Presi\ndent's temperature to be nor\ngnal. blood pressure to be\n130 80 and pulse 64 and regu\nlar He had no abnormal signs\nor symptoms other than A mild\naphasia (difficulty In speaking).\nThe President had no head\nache. nausea, vomiting, im\npairment of consciousness or\nbreathing, convulsions, stifTness\nof the neck, paralysis, oj\nnormal reflexes.\nThe President, following,da lid\nsedation, slept through the af\nternoon, except during exami\nnations. and did not awaken\nunt|l 8 p.m. at Which time he\nenjoyed a light iupper in bed.\nFollowing this, the President\npicked up a Western novel, and\nread for half an hour.\nGen. Snyder later repeated\nthe mild sedation. The Presi\ndent went to sleep at 9 p.m.\nand slept quietly until 5 a.m.\nthis morning. He remained\nquietly in bed until 7:15 a.m..\nat which time he was again\nexamined by his attending\nphysicians. The physical and\nneurological examination again\nshowed no abnormalities other\nthan a slight impairment in\nspeech. This had improved per\nceptibly during the intervening\nhours.\nThis confirm* our original\ndip gnosis that the President i i\nsuffered an occlusion of a small\nbranch of the middle cerebral i\nartery on the left side. It can- i\nnot be determined at this time\nwhether the condition present j\nis one of a small clot or a j\nvascular spasm. All findings in\ndicate no brain hemorrhage.\nIt is possible that the chill\nthat the President experienced j\nyesterday noon was a contrib-\nuting factor in this instance.\nAlthough the present con-\ndition is mild and is expected\nto be transitory in nature, it\nwill require a period of rest and\nsubstantially decreased activity 1\nestimated at several weeks.\nHospitalization will not be nec- j\nessary. Dr. Francis M. Forster,\nprofessor of neurology and\ndean of Georgetown University\nMedical School in Washington. 1\nD. C.. and Dr. Houston H. Mer\nritt, professor of neurology of\nColumbia University Medical t\nSchool in New York City, have 1\nbeen requested to see the Pres- 1\nident in .consultation later t\ntoday. I\nIn the absence of other i\nfindings, the patient's age, and\nthe improvement that he has\nshown in the relatively short\nperiod since the onset of his\nillness, the outlook for com- 1\nplete recovery within a reason- 1\nable period of time is excellent.\nThe text of the medical I 1\nbulletin Issued at 6 p.m. yes- i\nter dap:\nThe President was seen in\nconsultation at 3:46 p.m. this\nafternoon by Dr. Francis M.\nForster, professor of neurology\nand dean of Georgetown Uni\nversity Medical School in\nWashington, D. C.; Dr. Houston\nH. Merritt, professor of neu\nrology of Columbia University\nMedical School in New York\nCity; Dr. James F. Hammill.\nassistant professor of neurology\nof Columbia University Med\nical School, along with Lt. Col. 1\nRoy E. Clausen, Jr., USA <MC>.'\nchief of neurology at Walter\nReed Hospital.\nThe following bulletin was\nissued by the neurological con-\n\u25a0ultants:\n\"The President has had an\nocclusion of a small branch of\na cerebral vessel which has\nproduced a slight difficulty in\nspeaking. There is no evidence\nof a cerebral hemorrhage or\nany serious lesion of the cere\nbral vessels. The difficulty in\nm\nDR. FRANCIS M. FORSTER\nGeorgetown Dean Called\n\u2014AP Photo\nspeaking has improved over the\nperiod of the last 24 hours and\nis now manifested only by a\nhesitancy in saying certain dif\nficult words. ReadiAg, writ\ning, and reasoning powers are\nnot affected.\n\"The President's physical\nstrength is normal, and he is\nallowed to be up and about his\nhome. Home surroundings are\nconsidered preferable to the\nhospital for recovery. He is\nalert, his spirits are good, and\nhe discussed with interest and\nclarity recent events.\n\"The present disability is\nmild and transitory in nature.\nWe feel that the original rec\nommendation for rest and de\ncrease in physical activity\nshould be followed.\u201d\nAll attending physicians and\nconsultants are agreed that the\nPresident has not had another\nheart attack and that the pres\nent symptoms have no rela\ntionship to his previous heart\nattack.\nTruman Wishes\nQuick Recovery\nFor Eisenhower\nINDEPENDENCE, Mo., Nov.\n27 (JP). \u2014Former President Tru\nman has expressed hope that\nPresident Eisenhower will re\noover quickly from his lafest\nillness and be able to \u201cresume\nfull direction of his office.\u201d\nMr. Truman said In a state\niment last night:\n\u201cI am shocked and disturbed\nby the news of the President\u2019s\nillness. I hope and pray for\nhis quick recovery. I know\nthe American people feel as I\ndo in wishing for him as Pres\nident and for him as a person\nthe speediest return to good\nhealth.\n\"At a time when we face\ncritical problems involving the\nsecurity of the free world we\nhave need for the constant\nvigilance of the Chief Execu\ntive, and we are most anxious\nfor him soon to resume full\ndirection of his office. In this\ntask he can count on the un\nderstanding and co-operation\nof everyone.\u201d I\nCourageous, Nixon Says\nAbout Mrs. Eisenhower\nBy the AHOClated Press i.\nFor the third time in 26\nmonths. Mrs. Dwight D. Elsen\nhower is watching over a sick\nhusband.\nVice President Nixon de- 1\nscribed as \"courageous\u201d her 1\naction Monday night in attend-\ning a state dinner for King\nMohamed V of Morocco, after\nPresident Eisenhower had suf\nfered a mild stroke.\n\u201cI sat by her and I know\nunder what stress she was,\u201d Mr\nNixon said.\nBut last night, Mrs. Eisen\nhower joined the ailing Pres\nident in dining from trays and\nwatching television for a couple\nof hours in their White House\nliving quarters.\nBefore the Monday night\ndinner, the White House had\nannounced only that Mr. Eisen\nhower had suffered \u201ca chill.\u201d:\nBut lt was disclosed yesterday\nthat tentative diagnosis already\nhad been made of a blockage of\na small brain artery com\nmonly called a little stroke.\nPraised by Nixon\nMr. Nixon, who escorted the\nFirst Lady to the dinner, com\nmented\n\"I might say that Mrs. Eisen\nhower's performance last\ni Monday night, knowing\nwhat she knew, was as coura\ngous as I have ever seen by any\none. It was perhaps the most\ndifficult time she has ever had.'\nNo state functions interfered\nduring Mr. Eisenhower's previ\nous illnesses\u2014a heart attack in\nDenver in September 1955 and\nan ileitis operation in June\n1956. In each case. Mrs. Eisen\nhower took a room in the hospi\ntal to be near the President,\nand remained with him through\nconvalescence.\nShe herself underwent an\noperation last August, lemain\ning in Waltew\u00dfeed Hospital for\n25 days.\nj Some Events Canceled\nHow closely she will stay\nwith the President in the White\ni House apparently depends on\nt how rapidly he recovers Some\ni scheduled events already have\ni been canceled or postponed.\nThe White House said there Is\nr no immediate information on\nwhat others may be changed,\ni A short time before the nature\nVascular Spasm Known\nCommonly as Stroke\nBy JOHN M. ROSSON\nIf it had happened to anyone else, the nature of President\nEisenhower\u2019s illness\u2014in one respect still up in the air\u2014prob\nably would have been described by the casual observer im\nmediately after his attack on Monday as a slight stroke.\nAs it is. two specialists in necrology who examined the\nPresident late yesterday, drew a finer line and diagnosed his\ntrouble as a. blood clot or vas\ncular spasm in the brain.,\nWashington physicians fa-\nmiliar with such cases also in\nsisted today there is a differ\nence, even if the illness in some\n\u201cless attention-getting\u2019\u2019 case is\nsometimes \u201coff-handedly\u201d called\na stroke.\nProbably because of the fear\nassociated with the word. White\nHouse sources, joined by ex\nperienced doctors, hastily\npointed out that strokes usually\nmean the destruction of brain\nmatter, while clots and vascu\nlar spasms, if fleeting enough,\ncan come and go without per-\nmanent damage.\nt\nStronger Sequel Possible\nThey foresaw for the Presi\ndent a relatively speedy recov\nery, with his difficulty in speak\ning a \u201ctransitory\u201d matter.\nOther physicians, however,\nexpressed the opinion that \u201cnow\nthat he\u2019s had the first such in\ncident,\u201d the possibility of an\nother one is increased, with a\n10 per cent chance that the 1\nsecond one would be more\nserious.\nAfter Dr. Francis M. Forster,\nprofessor of neurology and dean\nof \u2018he Georgetown University\nMedical School here, and Dr.\nH. M. Merritt, professor of\nneurology at Columbia Univer\nsity Medical School, New York,\ncompleted their examination of\nthe President about 6 o'clock\nlast night, the White House\nissued a three paragraph an\nnouncement.\nIllness Detailed\nThe first paragraph described\nthe details of the illness:\n\u201cThe President has had an\nocclusion (blockage) of a small\nbranch to a cerebral vessel\n(or artery) which has produced\na slight difficulty in speaking.\nThere is no evidence of a cere\nbral hemorrhage or any seri\nous lesion of the cerebral ves\nsels. The difficulty in speaking\nhas improved over the period of\nthe last 24 hours and is now\nmanifested only by a hesitancy\nin saying certain difficult\nwords. Reading, writing and\nreasoning powers are not af\nfected.\u201d\nAn Earlier announcement had\nsaid it had not been determined\nas yet \u201cwhether the condition\npresent is one of a small clot\nor a vascular spasm.\u201d\nSix Cerebral Arteries\nDrawing on those two par\nagraphs, specialists in both\nprivate practice and at the\nNational Institute of Health\nhere pieced together what they\nbelieve happened to the Presi\ndent:\nEvery normal human being\nhas three cerebral arteries on\neach side of the brain (there\nfore six altogether) which feed\nthe brain nourishing blood.\nTaking just one side, the\nleft, the one involved in the\ni President\u2019s case, they are the\nleft anterior artery, which feeds\nthe front portion of the brain,\nthe left posterior artery, which\nfeeds the rear portion of the\nbrain, and the left middle ar\ntery, which feeds the middle\nportion of the brain.\nTogether, with the help of\"\nmany minute branches on each,\nthey control the body's actions.\nIt was one of the many mi-\nof Mr. Eisenhower\u2019s illness was\nannounced yesterday, Mrs.\nMary Jane McCaffree. the\nFirst Lady\u2019s secretary, was tell\ning newspaperwomen about two\nluncheons on Mrs. Eisenhower\u2019s\ncalendar for next week. There i\nwas no later announcement\nwhether the dates would be\nkept.\nThese changes were an\nnounced;\n1. The Eisenhowers will not\nattend a dinner, scheduled to\nnight in their honor, by the\nKing of Morocco.\n2. A diplomatic-military re\nception set for next Tuesday\nat the White House has been\npostponed. That event was\nto start the 1957-8 social\nseason at the mansion.\n1 3 The President of Chile has\ncanceled his state visit, set for\nearly December.\nSAVING I\nFor Old Age\n...For Emergencies\nFor Future Purchases\nFor Peace of Mind\nNA. 8-7300 I\nA?'flj6inglon'* Oldest \u25a0piip!;\nString! end ISpte:\nl.onn Assncielinn j\nUUaU^UjjJI\nnute branches of the left mid\ndle artery (one of many which\nhelp to control speech) to\nwhich \"something\u201d happened\nto cause the President's illness.\nThe \u201csomething,\u201d the doctors\nagree, was either a clot or a\nvascular spasm. Whichever it\nwas, (examining physicians\nhave left that point up in the\nair) it caused an occlusion of\nthe tiny branch artery.\nEncouraging Outlook\nOne. physician said \u201cthe out\nlook for this kind of thing is\nvery encouraging. It\u2019s a very\ncommon type of problem for\nwhich recovery is expected in\nthe majority of cases.\u201d\nReferring to the clotting of a\nsmall vessel\u2014whether the clot\noriginates from the heart\nchamber, or develops as an\nentirely separate process\u2014the\ndoctors agreed for the most\npart that either is less dan\ngerous than the \u201ckind of stroke\ncondition\" that develops from\nhigh blood pressure, which us\nually means a breaking of the\nvessel or artery and causes a'\ncerebral hemorrhage.\nSpasm Explained\nThey described a vascular\nspasm as a narrowing or con-:\nstriction of an artery, which'\ncan Impair the flow of blood\ntemporarily without blocking\nthe vessel entirely, as would a 1\nclot.\nSince the President's speech!\nreportedly is improving, there;\nwas a growing belief, therefore,\nthat his illness was caused by\na vascular spasm. It could or\ncould not, Urey added, be an\naftermath of the President\u2019s\npast heart attacks.\nThe exact diagnosis is dif\nficult to reach, they pointed j\nout, because the affected loca\ntion of the present difficulty\nwould be hard to pinpoint even\nwith X-rays.\nWhite Declines\nTo Discuss Illness\nOs Eisenhower\nBOSTON, Nov. 27 (JP).\u2014 Dr.\nPaul Dudley White, heart spe\ncialist who treated President\nEisenhower after his 1955 heart\nattack, said last night he has\nhad no official report from the\nWhite House dh the Presi\ndent\u2019s current illness.\nDr. White told newsmen he\nwould have no comment until\nhe had time to study the medl\ncal bulletins.\nIn a statement Dr. White:\nsaid:\n\u201cI have been busily occupied\nwith patients after a trip to\nSouth America. I have had no\nopportunity even to read the\nnewspapers, which I hope to\ndo. Until I have studied the\nmedical bulletins I will have\nnothing to say.\u201d\nBRITISH PAPERS\nTHINK PRESIDENT\nWILL QUIT OFFICE\nLONDON, Nov. 27 (IP).\u2014\nSome newspapers predicted\ntoday that President Eisen\nhower would be the first\nUnited States President to\nresign from office.\nShocked and saddened\nby news of Mr. Eisen\nhower\u2019s illness, Western\nEurope halfway expected\nan early announcement\nthat the ailing 61-year-old\nPresident had turned over\nthe United States Gov\nernment to Vice President\nNixon.\nThe press filled inside\npages with lengthy feature\narticles and personality\nsketches on Mr. Nixon.\nThe lead story in the\nLondon Evening News said\n\u201cthe big question in Wash\nington today is: Will\nPresident Eisenhower re\nsign?\"\nIn a dispatch from\nWashington the Daily\nExpress said;\n\u201cPresident Eisenhower's\nlatest illness almost cer\ntainly means that he will\nquit the White House\u2014\nboth for his own sake, and\nfor his country's sake.\nONE OF MANY BRANCH ARTERIES OF THE\nMIDDLE CEREBRAL ARTERY. ONE OF WHICH\nCAUSED THE PRESIDENTS ILLNESS\nleft artery\n\u2022-EFT\nANTERIOR /f ftZ\u2014Ljry (/rs,\\\nCEREBRAL Y>\\\nARTERY X\nCONNECTION WITH\nS SPINAL CORD LEFT POSTERIOR\nQ I CEREBRAL\nAFFECTED BRAIN AREA\u2014This sketch, an, over\nsimplification of the arteries supplying blood to the\nbrain, locates the left middle cerebral artery (cen\nter). It is one of the small branches in this middle\nsystem that is believed affected in President Elsen\nhower\u2019s illness, thus causing the President\u2019s speech\nimpediment.\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nCapital Leaders Voice\nConcern for President\nBy the Associated Frees I\nConcern for President Eisen\nhower\u2019s health was unanimous\nin Washington today, crossing\nparty lines and reaching into!\nall corners of the Government.\nSenator Lyndon B. Johnson,\nDemocrat of Texas, interrupted\nproceedings of his Senate mis\nsile investigation yesterday af\nternoon to fead.a news bulletin\non the President\u2019s latest attack.\n\u201cThis is very distressing news\nto all of us,\u201d said Senator\nJohnson, the Democratic leader\nof the Senate.\nHe added he was sure he ex\npressed the feelings of the\nwhole committee in voicing the\nhope the President\u2019s condition\n\u201cis not serious.\u201d\n\u201cThe President has the pray\ners of all of us for his com\nplete recovery,\u201d Senator John\nson said.\nSenator Saltonstall, Repub\nlican of Massachusetts, added\nthat Senator Johnson reflected\nhts own sentiment.\nBigger Nixon Rule Urged\nSenator Bridges of New\nHampshire, chairman of the\nG. O. P. Policy Committee in\nthe Senate, said he believed\nVice President Nixon should do\nall he can to fulfill the Presi\ndent's duties during the next\nfew' weeks.\nBut he said he believed the\nVice President would be rrtuc\ntant to do so unless strongly\nurged.\nHouse Speaker Rayburn\ncommented at his home near\nBonham, Tex.: \u201cI do trust and\npray that lt is not too serious\nand that he will have a speedy\nrecovery.\u201d\nSenator Kefauver of Tennes\n\u25a0HMBBy SALAMI \u201879I f W|\nAteffiSSs PASTRAMMomo BBfcF *\"*\u00a79* iLJI\n0 OOROWM BAR-B-QBEEF VHH\nMlMlJto tTeo NOVA LOX* \u00bbW <s3* f\nTMIIIKIIIIVIfIu 69*\nI \u2022mts.cAK\u00df \u00dcBWHITEFISH Ve 1\na. SP- ffLS-Z Pic kl6oLOXe-ONIONS Jt i\nloxwiNQ9\u2122\u201c:\"\nOut! 9Mt rljS'lmim Z cream cheesev>334 1\nMAJsSiJX WFT AMERICAN mSk'\"2V\nt is?SL a w\u00ab>L mm a1 m pickled tomatoes 3\u201d*2.3\u00ab I\nI 1 our, kjtch&ns m\nBorneo\ni BBrMT hDivpid KnreMtS ik 59* h\nI oKcASI l/OLNCtS HEALTH SALAD Z9< R\u00bbD 49 1\nI mw i i\n\u25a0Shouldersibks*79\u00ab rib cim steak?* 19^ I\nCHUCK RDASTwm 33*\nlonoon broil 79* chuck steaks*- 1 m\nKALKES 69\u00ab ROaBPSTK.ROAU\u00bb\u00bb\u00bb79cI=\ni ALL BEEF HAMBUR&E* \"W 1\nI %SBSS^BEEF\n3 FPxYERS SST*S\u00bb j I ifLAJgD \u25baTATOES lO*n 39*\nchicken le<is 53* breasts **79\u2018 M g **udoMt* PASCAL CELERY m\npP OARTOT9 15 APPLES 2/29*\nE FASHIONED EGG NOGr io* 69* E\nj.I)WW)Ju I I tssst* STRAWBERRIES SW\n\"\u201c\u2019BROWN BREADS\nl, u \u25a0~\u201c\u00bb4WEET POTATOEd's 5/4 I\nZ. SALAD DRESSING\nfIviNTL POLISH ,Z 3* KOTQ 2 N<\u00ab\n81 JBG snCAH oxanuiatid 49c iu\u00abimn tat Maw 70-\n|mi PINNER ROLISa\u00bb 29<r3 l A kT7iktw\nPOSIW9\u2019 FRUIT CLKI X>MS& #ULLI lOObftq/lQ* I\nli \u00bbMOt WTH PR/CSS TU CIOS/*4 St/// DEO!**\nsee, the 1956 Democratic vice\npresidential nominee, also said\nhe hopes the President's, attack\nwill not be serious and that he\nwill recover soon.\n\u201cWith the NATO council\nmeeting coming up in Decem\nber and the critical state 'of\n(the world, the President\u2019s good\nhealth and leadership are vital\n|ly needed,!\u2019 Senator Kefauver\nsaid. \u201cWe all pray for the best.\u201d\nSenator Carroll, Democrat of\nColorado, said, \u201cI hope and\npray President Elsenhower will\nregain hit health quickly.\u201d\nSenator Carroll said that\nwhether Vice President Nixon\nshould substitute for Mr. Elsen\nl hower at the scheduled confer\nences with congressional lead\ners next week raises \u201ca deli\ncate question.\u201d\nNATO Problem Discussed\nAs for the NATO conference\nlater next month. Senator Car\nroll said that, in the absence of\nMr. Elsenhower, it would be\nbest \u201cto leave it in the hands\nof Mr. Dulles and Mr. Steven\nson.\u201d\nOther comment:\nSenator Barrett, Republican\nof Wyoming: \u201cI am terribly\ndisturbed and am hoping and\npraying that it won\u2019t prove to\n!be serious and that the Presi\ndent, after a week or two, will\nbe able to return to his duties\nas Chief Executive. The news\nis a terrible shock, and all of\nus are rather alarmed at the\nturn of events.\u201d\nSenator Stennis. Democrat\nof Mississippi: \u201cWe are all\ndeeply concerned. We all pray\nthat he may recover fully. His\nillness sounds quite serious.\u201d\nSenator Bush, Republican of\nForeign Offices Slow\nTo on Illness\nBy RICHARD FRYKLUND\nEuropean Correspondent of The Star\nLONDON, Nov. 27.\u2014The confusion and the uncertainty\nin European capitals following reports last night on President\nElsenhower\u2019s Illness is a measure of the Importance to the\nwhole world of the American presidency,\nForeign Offices were slow to react. Officials here and\nIn Paris, Bonn, Rome and The Hague were ready with expres-\nsions of sympathy to the\nPresident and his family. But\nthey were still thinking of the\nfull Implications of the situa\ntion.\nThere were two questions:\n1. Should the summit meet\ning in Paris go on as scheduled\nwithout Mr. Eisenhower?\n2. How will the picture\nchange if Vice President Nixon\nfills in at the conference\u2014and\nperhaps takes over the presi\ndency?\nIn Rome, Paris and London\nsome unofficial government\nspokesmen said they doubted\nthe value of a summit meeting\nif the head of the biggest ally is\nnot present. They frankly\ndidnjt know how the picture\nwould change if Mr. Nixon\nwere to take over.\nThere was much speculation\nIn Europe about Mr. Nixon.\nPersona questioned In London\nstreets and shops this morning\nsaid they knew little about Mr.\nNixon but hopedbhe would be\na vigorous leader. Most per\nsons seemed to assume that\u2014\nas one put It: \u201cIt\u2019s three times\nand out of White House isn\u2019t:\nit?\u201d\nLondon papers are full of Ei\nsenhower and Nixon stories.\nMost papers had banner head\nlines. Four papers worded\ntheirs exactly (dike: \u201cIke has\na stroke.\u201d\nPeople here seem to believe\nConnecticut: \"I am\ndisturbed by today\u2019s news of\nthe President\u2019s Alness, and\nknow that the people of Con\nnecticut will join me In prayers\nI for his speedy and full re-:\ncovery.\u201d\nGov. Luther H. Hodges of>\nNorth Carolina said: \u201cLike all\nNorth Carolinians, I am deeply\nconcerned with the news of\nthe President\u2019s illness. I hope\nvery much that his illness is!\nnot serious, and wish for him\na complete and rapid recovery.\"\nThe Story About\nKODACHROME and KODACOLOR Processing\nUntil recently the rolor films. Kodachrome and lCodacolor. produced by\nhastman Kodak Company, wera sold with the coat of processing In\ncluded In the selling price. The processing was an exclusive service of\nEastman Kodak Company.\nRecently the Government ruled that all photo flnlshera had equal rights\nwith Eastman Kodak Company In processlni these Blms lor the public.\nIn en effort to secure your patronage, some companies have offered lower\nprices, hurry-up service end other Inducements.\nBased on our experience lt Is our opinion that the service and quality\nprovided by Eastman Kodak Company with Its many years of research\nand development Is the best processing service available.\nWe recommend that you continue to have your Kodak Aims processed\nBY THE MANUFACTURER. Eastman Kodak Company through Sommers,\nyour Kodak dealer.\nSOMMERS CAMERA\n715 14fh St.N.W. NSXT TO TWA AIRLINE ME. 8-5155\n\u2022\u2022wgwv \"V* V WIVM vnpt VO\nthe Illness is more serious than\nWhite House reports say. One\nLondon paper, the conserva\ntive Dispatch, says flatly, \u201cal\nmost certainly lt means that he\nwill quit the White House.\u201d\nThe papers emphasise that\nthis Is a time of crisis for West\nern defense and that strong\nleadership from the United\nStates Is necessary. But they\nare uncertain that there will\nbe such leadership for some\nweeks and don\u2019t know what can\ntake Its place.\nChurchill Cited\nBy Neurologist as\nRecovery Example\nBOSTON, Nov. 27 OP).\u2014Sir\nWinston Churchill\u2019s recovery\nfrom a stroke in 1953 Is cited\ni by a Boston neurologist to sup\nport hopes President Elsen\nhower can resume his full du\nties as chief executive.\nDr. Raymond D. Adams, chief\njofeneurology at Massachusetts\nGeneral Hospital, told the Bos\nton Globe \u201cthere is no need to\ndespair.\u201d\nHe recalled that Mr. Church\nill was stricken with a similar\nattack which Impaired his\nspeech.\n\u201cChurchill has been able to\njmake very fine orations and to\nI write very effectively since,\u201d\nDr. Adams said.\n\u201cThere are many instances\nwhere people have had this\nkind of thing and have been\nable to return to full service\nwith highly responsible duties.\u201d\nDr. Adams said .it is Impos\nsible at present to determine\nwhether the President\u2019s mild\nstroke would prevent him from\nperforming his duties. He said\nIhe kneW of cases where a per\nson who could not speak a\nword one day would be able to\nspeak normally the next.","height":"28947","width":"18151"}}
